WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:04.400
So WebR is a version of R compiled to run in a browser.

00:00:04.400 --> 00:00:08.280
You might want to use the containerization or sandboxing abilities of a browser.

00:00:08.280 --> 00:00:13.580
You might want to run sort of literate programming type things where you weave software and documentation

00:00:13.580 --> 00:00:17.200
together into a single object, or even reproducible output.

00:00:17.200 --> 00:00:21.959
You might have some data science you want in a nice package that is online, or you might

00:00:21.959 --> 00:00:25.840
just be interested in universal binaries, the idea of running a piece of software on

00:00:25.840 --> 00:00:29.400
lots of different machines that could even be mobile phones or tablets.

00:00:29.400 --> 00:00:34.599
These are all great reasons that I'm not going to talk about.

00:00:34.599 --> 00:00:38.959
Today I'm going to talk about why I wrote WebR, and it was actually for my previous

00:00:38.959 --> 00:00:41.919
life as an academic.

00:00:41.919 --> 00:00:46.919
So when I worked for Newcastle University, one of the things I did was I taught R to

00:00:46.919 --> 00:00:47.919
students.

00:00:47.919 --> 00:00:51.799
And at the end of the semester, one of the things we do is we evaluate what the students

00:00:51.799 --> 00:00:52.799
have learned.

00:00:52.799 --> 00:00:57.000
And we do that by asking them to write some R code, and we evaluate how well that R code

00:00:57.000 --> 00:00:58.000
runs.

00:00:58.400 --> 00:01:03.200
Now, during the pandemic, we had to do that on devices that we had no control over, people's

00:01:03.200 --> 00:01:07.080
home devices, things where R might not even be installed.

00:01:07.080 --> 00:01:11.120
We even had students doing exams, very important exams, on a mobile phone, which is not the

00:01:11.120 --> 00:01:12.919
best thing to do.

00:01:12.919 --> 00:01:16.839
So the question was, how do we capture that R code and make sure they're doing the right

00:01:16.839 --> 00:01:17.839
thing?

00:01:17.839 --> 00:01:21.839
Our first idea was actually quite good.

00:01:21.839 --> 00:01:27.720
We set a server up that sits and listens for students' R code, runs it, works out what

00:01:27.720 --> 00:01:29.879
the answer is, and then sends it back.

00:01:29.879 --> 00:01:37.680
So this way, we could give the student a website, the standard way of evaluating and

00:01:37.680 --> 00:01:40.599
assessing our students' works.

00:01:40.599 --> 00:01:44.680
And we just plugged into it this service, so it sends the code away, remembers what

00:01:44.680 --> 00:01:48.400
the student did, marks it, and then sends the answer back.

00:01:48.400 --> 00:01:51.279
And at first glance, it's really nice, because the student's just writing R code, and they're

00:01:51.279 --> 00:01:52.279
just seeing the results.

00:01:52.279 --> 00:01:53.559
They're happy.

00:01:53.559 --> 00:01:54.839
So we tested it.

00:01:54.839 --> 00:01:56.000
It worked.

00:01:56.000 --> 00:02:00.160
We put it into production, and the first thing that happened was the server crashed.

00:02:00.160 --> 00:02:04.300
It fell over, and I had a room full of very angry students.

00:02:04.300 --> 00:02:06.199
So that was not ideal.

00:02:06.199 --> 00:02:08.320
This was just before the Christmas break.

00:02:08.320 --> 00:02:12.360
So I went away over Christmas, and I thought, okay, well, what can I do to solve this?

00:02:12.360 --> 00:02:17.759
And one of the ideas I had was to instead evaluate that R code locally inside the web

00:02:17.759 --> 00:02:19.960
browser instead of using a server.

00:02:19.960 --> 00:02:23.919
And this makes sense, because it means you're dividing the load over lots of different machines

00:02:24.199 --> 00:02:28.199
instead of depending on that one machine.

00:02:28.199 --> 00:02:32.279
So the way this works is that there's a technology called WebAssembly that's been around a few

00:02:32.279 --> 00:02:37.080
years now, but is getting more popular very recently.

00:02:37.080 --> 00:02:39.919
What it is is a portable binary code format.

00:02:39.919 --> 00:02:44.639
It's a bit like JavaScript, but when it's in a certain format, you can't read it properly.

00:02:44.639 --> 00:02:50.360
It runs in the browser, and what it does is enable high-performance applications to run

00:02:50.360 --> 00:02:54.399
in a web browser at almost native speed.

00:02:54.399 --> 00:03:02.399
It's supported by most modern browsers, and you can kind of think of it as Java, but good.

00:03:02.399 --> 00:03:05.440
The next thing that would make this work is Inscripten.

00:03:05.440 --> 00:03:11.940
Inscripten is a compiler for WebAssembly, so it converts C code into WebAssembly.

00:03:11.940 --> 00:03:12.940
It's based on LLVM.

00:03:12.940 --> 00:03:19.720
Again, it's been around for a few years, and successfully used in a few projects, along

00:03:19.720 --> 00:03:24.000
with spoiler alert, sorry, Winston.

00:03:24.000 --> 00:03:26.820
And also, Inscripten should work like this.

00:03:26.820 --> 00:03:31.880
You give it two commands, there's two commands, emconfigure, emmake, you give it C code, and

00:03:31.880 --> 00:03:34.919
a WebAssembly package falls out.

00:03:34.919 --> 00:03:36.880
When it works, it's absolute magic.

00:03:36.880 --> 00:03:38.960
It's incredible.

00:03:38.960 --> 00:03:39.960
It just works.

00:03:39.960 --> 00:03:42.460
You get some C code, and it runs online.

00:03:42.460 --> 00:03:44.300
But there's a problem.

00:03:44.300 --> 00:03:46.759
Because R uses Fortran code.

00:03:46.759 --> 00:03:50.960
Some of the code it's inherited had original releases that were in the 70s.

00:03:50.960 --> 00:03:56.960
And even worse, Inscripten can't directly compile Fortran code.

00:03:56.960 --> 00:03:58.759
Notice I say directly.

00:03:58.759 --> 00:03:59.759
Because there's a trick.

00:03:59.759 --> 00:04:03.919
Unfortunately, the trick makes things a little bit more complicated.

00:04:03.919 --> 00:04:06.000
It looks like that.

00:04:06.000 --> 00:04:07.119
I'm not going to go into detail.

00:04:07.119 --> 00:04:08.119
It's very messy.

00:04:08.119 --> 00:04:10.279
There is a link there if you're interested in learning more.

00:04:10.279 --> 00:04:14.199
I will point out, I think I've got time, really quickly, that there is a point in that graph

00:04:14.199 --> 00:04:16.200
that says choose your own chaos.

00:04:16.200 --> 00:04:20.480
And that's because you choose between using an ancient version of GCC or an unreleased

00:04:20.480 --> 00:04:21.799
version of LLVM.

00:04:21.799 --> 00:04:24.799
So pick your poison.

00:04:24.799 --> 00:04:25.799
It does work.

00:04:25.799 --> 00:04:27.239
There's a Web site.

00:04:27.239 --> 00:04:30.679
You can go to it, and you can run it on the browser.

00:04:30.679 --> 00:04:35.760
I would say do it now, but the conference Wi-Fi is a bit iffy, and it is quite a big

00:04:35.760 --> 00:04:36.760
package that downloads.

00:04:36.760 --> 00:04:37.760
So it may not work.

00:04:37.760 --> 00:04:41.079
But when you get home, go to the Web site, try it out.

00:04:41.079 --> 00:04:42.079
You can load packages.

00:04:42.079 --> 00:04:47.640
I've built just enough of the tidyverse so you can load ggplot in the browser and make

00:04:47.640 --> 00:04:48.640
a plot.

00:04:48.640 --> 00:04:49.640
It looks like that.

00:04:49.640 --> 00:04:50.640
And, yeah.

00:04:50.640 --> 00:04:51.640
It just works.

00:04:51.640 --> 00:04:52.640
Thank you very much.

00:04:52.640 --> 00:04:52.640


